The process areas and tank farm areas also have passive mitigation systems, such as liquid release containment systems.  These systems consist of diked areas, which would contain any spilled material and limit the effects on the environment.  The design of these diked areas reduces the total surface area of the spill, thus, reducing the evaporation rate of the spilled material.  In most cases, these diked areas may reduce the evaporation rate by a factor of 10, which reduces the distance to the endpoints associated with an accidental release.



Chemical specific prevention steps have also been enacted and include the following:



Plant-wide:



-Specially trained on-site Emergency Response Team which includes a Fire Brigade and Spill Response Team;

-Ability to apply vapor and/or fire suppression foam;

-Implementation of an effective Behavior-Based Safety program.



Carbon Disulfide: 



-Use of a double-walled tank with a vacuum on the outer-shell to detect failure of tank;

-Storage tank not vented to atmosphere; sealed vessel;

-Individual liquid containment system (dike) constructed;

-Overfill protection systems in place;

-Maintenance of a water layer in dike area to act as a blanket on any released carbon disulfide (carbon disulfide is much heavier than water, tends to sink beneath water);

-Installation of a liquid carbon disulfide detector in diked area to trigger a DCS alarm; 

-Limited use of flan

ged connections, reduced chance of leak in transfer lines;

-Check valves installed to mitigate contamination of other systems;

-ISO 9001 procedures in place governing operations associated with carbon disulfide;

-Compatible materials of construction utilized;

-Process included in Mechanical Integrity program;

-Use of inert gas for flammable material transfer;

-Multiple Process Hazard Analyses completed for carbon disulfide systems.



Cyclohexylamine:



-Storage tank not vented to atmosphere; sealed vessel;

-Liquid containment system (dike) constructed;

-Limited use of flanged connections, reduced chance of leak in transfer lines;

-ISO 9001 procedures in place governing operations associated with cyclohexylamine;

-Compatible materials of construction utilized;

-Process included in Mechanical Integrity program;

-Overfill protection systems in place;

-Process Hazard Analyses completed for cyclohexylamine systems.



Dimethylamine:  



-Storage tank(s)not vented to atmosphere; sealed vessel;

-Liquid containment system (dike) constructed;

-Limited use of flanged connections, reduced chance of leak in transfer lines;

-Check valves installed to mitigate contamination of other systems;

-Check valve installed to minimize release of material in the event of an unloading line failure;

-ISO 9001 procedures in place governing operations associated with dimethylamine;

-Compatible materials of construction utilized;

-Process included in Mechanical Integrity program;

-Overfill protection systems in place;

-Installed new process vessel, replacing an older vessel;

-Multiple Process Hazard Analyses completed for dimethylamine systems.



Epichlorohydrin:



-Storage tank vented to thermal oxidizer air pollution control device;

-Detonation arrestor installed on vent line to thermal oxidizer;

-Liquid containment system (dike) constructed;

-Check valves installed to mitigate contamination of other systems;

-ISO 9001 procedures in place governing operatio

ns associated with epichlorohydrin;

-Compatible materials of construction utilized;

-Process included in Mechanical Integrity program;

-Overfill protection systems in place;

-Multiple Process Hazard Analyses completed for epichlorohydrin systems.



Formaldehyde:



-Storage tank vented to thermal oxidizer air pollution control device;

-Detonation arrestor installed on vent line to thermal oxidizer;

-Liquid containment system (dike) constructed;

-Check valves installed to mitigate contamination of other systems;

-ISO 9001 procedures in place governing operations associated with formaldehyde;

-Compatible materials of construction utilized;

-Process included in Mechanical Integrity program;

-Overfill protection systems in place;

-New tank installed;

-Multiple Process Hazard Analyses completed for formaldehyde systems.



Monomethylamine:  



-Storage tank not vented to atmosphere; sealed vessel;

-Individual liquid containment system (dike) constructed;

-Maintenance of a water layer in diked are to absorb released material;

-Limited use of flanged connections, reduced chance of leak in transfer lines;

-Check valves installed to mitigate contamination of other systems;

-Check valve installed to minimize release of material in the event of an unloading line failure;

-ISO 9001 procedures in place governing operations associated with monomethylamine;

-Compatible materials of construction utilized;

-Process included in Mechanical Integrity program;

-Overfill protection systems in place;

-Multiple Process Hazard Analyses completed for monomethylamine systems.



Phosphorous Trichloride:  



-Storage tank enclosed and located in a diked area to reduce emissions to air in the event of a storage tank failure;

-Individual liquid containment system (dike) constructed;

-Storage tank not vented to atmosphere; sealed vessel;

-Limited use of flanged connections, reduced chance of leak in transfer lines;

-ISO 9001 procedures in place governing operat

ions associated with phosphorous trichloride;

-Compatible materials of construction utilized;

-Process included in Mechanical Integrity program;

-Overfill protection systems in place;

-Emergency response drills practiced concerning phosphorous trichloride releases;

-Vapor control foam available to suppress vapors from a spill;

-Installed pressure relief catch-pot, vented to scrubber system;

-Multiple Process Hazard Analyses completed for phosphorous trichloride systems.





The Buckman Laboratories Cadet, Missouri facility has not had an accidental release, as defined under 40 CFR 68.42(a), from a covered process in the most recent five years.



Buckman Laboratories, Inc. emergency response program for the Cadet Plant is based upon the National Response Team's Integrated Contingency Plan developed in 1996 by the EPA, OSHA, DOT, MMS and Coast Guard.  The emergency response plan for the Cadet Plant has been distributed to the Washington County Sheriffs Department, the Potosi Fire Protection District, and the Local Emergency Planning Committee.  Several individuals associated with the Potosi Fire Department are current or past associates of Buckman Laboratories and members of the Cadet Plant's Fire Brigade, and can offer invaluable emergency response assistance.
